Ok ðŸ˜“ I found the problem. It was the chained methods of sharp to resize the image. This is weird, because I thought that the resize after composite does not affect to the composite operation. My solution is to convert it to buffer between composite and resize.

**does not work**

```js
const badge = createBadge(); /* buffer */
let icon = sharp('./icon.png');
icon = icon.composite([{ input: badge, top: 0, left: 0, blend: 'over' }]);
icon = icon.resize(200, 200);
icon.png().toFile('./result.png');
```

Because the resize only affect to the source image. The composite seems to be completed after the resize. You can see it if you resize it with a size of greater that the badge. e.g. resize it to 512 px. You see that the badge is not resized.

**this works**

```js
const badge = createBadge(); /* buffer */
let icon = await sharp('./icon.png').toBuffer();
icon = await sharp(icon).composite([{ input: badge, top: 0, left: 0, blend: 'over' }]).toBuffer();
icon = await sharp(icon).resize(200, 200).toBuffer();
sharp(icon).png().toFile('./result.png');
```

Use `toBuffer` to snapshot the state.
Q: Why not chained directly? A: Because if-conditions in the original code.
Q: Why does my demo project work? You said: Same code. A: Yes, but focused on the composite method, because this was the error. I successively tested the code. I resized a lot of icons for Android. And some of them are smaller than the badge. And I didn't know that the composite is executed after resize, even if the order is composite().resize(). ...

Again: The resize after composite resizes the source image (icon) only. And the composite is executed after that. In this case, the resize method changed the size of the source image to 200px and executes the composite with the badge of 420px.
Note that `toBuffer` is async. I think this is the reason for sharp to behave like that. But I'm sure someone else can explain this better. Anyway... It works now. It's great that sharp can use svg and composite for dynamic auto-generated stuff. â¤ï¸

@lovell the issue was probably closed too fast by the author.  
Calling `composite(...).resize(...).png()` (and possibly other methods considering @grdnkln example) will trigger an error if the post-composite image size is smaller than the composite input image size.
Looks like composite is applied after every other change in the chain.

