At first, we were doing:
```javascript
// sourceImageBuffer contains the bytes of the source image
const img = sharp(sourceImageBuffer);
const {width, height, hasAlpha} = await img.metadata();
if (!hasAlpha) {
  img.joinChannel(Buffer.alloc(width * height, 255), { raw: { width, height, channels: 1 }})
}
const decodedBuffer = await img.raw().toBuffer();
```

That works well for 3 and 4-channel images, but isn't working as expected for 1-channel grayscale images. That makes sense to me, as the `.joinChannel()` would add a second channel, not a fourth one.

I was able to make it work using code like this, but it seems rather awkward and possibly inefficient to me:

```javascript
// .raw() seems to automatically decode 1-channel to 3
let decoded = await sharp(sourceImageBuffer).raw().toBuffer({ resolveWithObject: true});
const {width, height, channels} = decoded.info;

// if there are still only 3 channels, add an opaque alpha channel
if (channels === 3) {
  decoded = await sharp(decoded.data, { raw: { width, height, channels }})
      .joinChannel(Buffer.alloc(width * height, 255), { raw: { width, height, channels: 1 }})
      .toBuffer({ resolveWithObject: true });
}

// decoded.data now has 4-channel RGBA bytes,
