Hello, the `width`, `height` and `channels` are required as additional parameters for raw pixel input as the Buffer contains only the pixel values.

Luckily the second parameter of the `toBuffer` callback contains what you need:

``` javascript
sharp('./input.png')
  .raw()
  .toBuffer(function(data, info) {
    sharp(rawBuf, { raw: info })...
  });
```

But when I use the promise, there is only one parameter passed from it, namely only the pixel values.
Wouldn't it make sense adding the info parameter also to the parameters passed?

``` js
var sharp = require('sharp');

sharp('./input.jpg')
.raw().toBuffer()
.then(function(rawBuf, rawInfo) {
  console.log(typeof rawBuf, typeof rawInfo); // object undefined
});
```

Edit: Would a "realize"([cb]) method make sense? One that performs all queued operations in-place (in the C implementation) - so one doesn't need to move the data around to a new sharp instance?

